1
00:00:16,760 --> 00:00:20,040
Written and Directed
by Grigory Alexandrov

2
00:00:20,520 --> 00:00:23,640
Music by Isaac Dunayevsky

3
00:00:24,160 --> 00:00:27,760
Camera - B. Petrov
Lyrics by V. Lebedev-Kumach

4
00:00:53,880 --> 00:00:55,160
Cast

5
00:00:55,760 --> 00:00:58,960
Young Composer - T. Shalaev
Secretary - M. Mironova

6
00:00:59,200 --> 00:01:02,400
Waiter - N. Kondratiev
Woodcutter - V. Sanayev

7
00:01:02,680 --> 00:01:05,880
Policeman - A. Dolinin
Olympiad officer - I. Chuvelev

8
00:01:06,840 --> 00:01:11,040
Dear viewers, we are calling
your attention to the prologue.

9
00:01:14,320 --> 00:01:17,040
Then we'll keep you
no longer.

10
00:01:19,120 --> 00:01:21,360
Come enjoy THE VOLGA-VOLGA.

11
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:26,640
VOLGA-VOLGA

12
00:01:30,480 --> 00:01:32,600
Musical comedy

13
00:01:34,240 --> 00:01:36,360
MOSFILM

14
00:01:37,200 --> 00:01:39,240
Allow us to introduce
the main characters.

15
00:01:40,720 --> 00:01:42,720
Byvalov - I. Ilyinsky

16
00:01:44,400 --> 00:01:47,560
The name Byvalov here stands
for Worldlywise.

17
00:01:51,200 --> 00:01:54,240
This bureaucrat is played
by Ilyinsky of all guys.

18
00:02:00,200 --> 00:02:04,000
The pilot is played by Volodin.
Good for him.

19
00:02:04,960 --> 00:02:09,040
Meet the merry Waterman
Enacted by Pavel Olenev.

20
00:02:09,480 --> 00:02:13,320
Sergei Antimonov - I swear! -
watches over public welfare.

21
00:02:13,840 --> 00:02:17,800
Accountant Alexei Trubyshkin -
Actor Andrei Tutyshkin.

22
00:02:18,760 --> 00:02:21,160
Letter-carrier - Lubov Orlova

23
00:02:23,040 --> 00:02:26,120
Letter-carrier Petrova,
Known here as Arrow,

24
00:02:29,600 --> 00:02:33,480
is played by Lubov Orlova

25
00:02:48,040 --> 00:02:50,160
Off we go.

26
00:03:23,400 --> 00:03:26,720
Nervous work is around here
on transport.

27
00:03:27,360 --> 00:03:30,160
Why nervous, you are just
lying here and smoking.

28
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:32,480
A fat lot do you know.

29
00:03:32,800 --> 00:03:34,640
I've been a pilot
for thirty years

30
00:03:34,960 --> 00:03:38,520
and I never knew fear,
but now I don't know

31
00:03:38,840 --> 00:03:40,760
if I'll come back home
safe or not.

32
00:03:41,640 --> 00:03:43,480
Is the river so dangerous?

33
00:03:43,800 --> 00:03:46,320
Oh no. The river is quiet.

34
00:03:46,840 --> 00:03:49,960
It's the wire hawzer.
It's dangerous.

35
00:03:57,640 --> 00:03:59,240
What did I say?

36
00:04:00,120 --> 00:04:03,280
We'll stand idle for 3 hours
and there's an express here.

37
00:04:03,600 --> 00:04:06,480
An express should be delivered
within 40 minutes.

38
00:04:08,960 --> 00:04:10,720
Uncle Kuzya!

39
00:04:12,920 --> 00:04:14,880
Help the Communication
Ministry out!

40
00:04:15,240 --> 00:04:17,640
- What?
- Go to Domestic industries.

41
00:04:18,320 --> 00:04:22,680
Tell them there's an express
for them on the ferry.

42
00:04:24,720 --> 00:04:26,120
Right. Gee-up.

43
00:04:29,800 --> 00:04:32,840
- An express for who?
- Byvalov.

44
00:04:33,560 --> 00:04:37,720
There'll be a thunder
for this express.

45
00:04:41,600 --> 00:04:42,880
Close the door!

46
00:04:43,200 --> 00:04:45,040
Comrade Byvalov is busy.

47
00:04:46,040 --> 00:04:48,840
Byvalov I. I., Dpt head
small domestic industries

48
00:04:50,840 --> 00:04:52,800
- No telegram?
- Not yet.

49
00:04:54,040 --> 00:04:55,480
I wonder.

50
00:04:55,800 --> 00:04:59,240
I know how you feel.
Your life is work.

51
00:04:59,640 --> 00:05:03,480
It's amazing. A man
of elemental work capacity...

52
00:05:06,440 --> 00:05:08,880
Comrade Byvalov, I am getting
married.

53
00:05:09,520 --> 00:05:11,240
- Oh no.
- Close the door.

54
00:05:13,960 --> 00:05:15,920
You say elemental...

55
00:05:16,400 --> 00:05:19,200
I mean a man of elemental
work capacity...

56
00:05:20,360 --> 00:05:21,880
Can I come in?

57
00:05:22,480 --> 00:05:25,160
Zoya, what is going on?
I can't work.

58
00:05:25,920 --> 00:05:29,520
I am telling you in plain Russian,
Comrade Byvalov is busy.

59
00:05:34,040 --> 00:05:36,200
So you say "work capacity".

60
00:05:36,560 --> 00:05:39,480
I've worked under your guidance
for five years.

61
00:05:39,800 --> 00:05:42,600
We have changed 20 institutions

62
00:05:43,360 --> 00:05:46,080
getting closer
to Moscow every day.

63
00:05:46,400 --> 00:05:48,480
And when there are

64
00:05:48,840 --> 00:05:52,120
only three or four kilometers
left to reach Moscow,

65
00:05:52,760 --> 00:05:54,960
the likes of you

66
00:05:57,360 --> 00:05:59,280
are transferred to...

67
00:06:00,080 --> 00:06:03,840
...to some absolutely small
domestic industry.

68
00:06:04,360 --> 00:06:07,880
I just want to fret and fume,
fret and fume.

69
00:06:14,200 --> 00:06:15,840
Zoya Ivanovna...

70
00:06:18,200 --> 00:06:20,360
I've told you nothing.

71
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:23,040
I'm waiting to be called
any minute.

72
00:06:23,440 --> 00:06:25,280
- From Moscow?
- From Moscow.

73
00:06:25,720 --> 00:06:27,520
- No telegram?
- Not yet.

74
00:06:27,960 --> 00:06:30,200
Really,
I want to fret and fume.

75
00:06:37,920 --> 00:06:40,760
You know what I want most
of all now?

76
00:06:41,240 --> 00:06:43,480
To fulfil your wishes.

77
00:06:44,240 --> 00:06:47,560
I would do whatever
you asked me to do.

78
00:06:48,320 --> 00:06:50,480
You'd ask - and I'd do it.

79
00:06:51,240 --> 00:06:53,840
You can ask me anything.

80
00:06:54,720 --> 00:06:58,760
Come to our rehearsal
from four to five.

81
00:07:00,040 --> 00:07:03,000
From 4 to 5? I can't.
I've got a rehearsal myself.

82
00:07:03,880 --> 00:07:05,800
- No hard feelings?
- None at all.

83
00:07:06,120 --> 00:07:09,760
Your rehearsal is my rehearsal.

84
00:07:10,160 --> 00:07:11,800
What are you--

85
00:07:12,240 --> 00:07:14,320
- What are you rehearsing today?
- Wagner.

86
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:16,880
How boring.

87
00:07:18,040 --> 00:07:20,000
- No hard feelings?
- None at all.

88
00:07:20,600 --> 00:07:22,880
You just know nothing about
classical music.

89
00:07:23,240 --> 00:07:25,480
Look, it's just wonderful.

90
00:07:28,560 --> 00:07:30,400
The Death of Isolde.

91
00:07:44,520 --> 00:07:46,880
The part of tuba
is extraordinary.

92
00:07:56,200 --> 00:07:58,160
One-two...

93
00:07:58,840 --> 00:08:02,240
A pause for 47 bars.
We don't play them.

94
00:08:02,560 --> 00:08:04,000
Why not?

95
00:08:19,680 --> 00:08:22,080
What do you say about
The Death of Isolde?

96
00:08:22,400 --> 00:08:24,800
- She dies too long.
- Classically.

97
00:08:28,800 --> 00:08:31,360
So you say an outstanding
executive.

98
00:08:31,400 --> 00:08:33,760
I say an outstanding
executive like you...

99
00:08:36,320 --> 00:08:38,240
Comrades, close the door.

100
00:08:38,760 --> 00:08:41,600
Comrade Byvalov, try
to see my point.

101
00:08:43,680 --> 00:08:45,720
I'm telling you again

102
00:08:46,240 --> 00:08:48,680
I am waiting to be called
to Moscow any minute.

103
00:08:48,960 --> 00:08:51,480
I've no time for trifles.

104
00:08:52,240 --> 00:08:54,760
Listen to this sound.

105
00:08:55,800 --> 00:08:57,160
Like from a log.

106
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:00,400
Sound... It takes an expert.

107
00:09:01,200 --> 00:09:03,680
I've played for 50 years.

108
00:09:13,520 --> 00:09:15,560
And I've never heard
such a bad sound.

109
00:09:15,800 --> 00:09:18,920
Ours is mass production.

110
00:09:19,640 --> 00:09:22,200
I can't afford to check

111
00:09:22,440 --> 00:09:24,880
every balalaika.

112
00:09:27,240 --> 00:09:29,920
I say, have you ever wanted

113
00:09:30,240 --> 00:09:31,720
to compose music yourself?

114
00:09:32,040 --> 00:09:33,800
Myself? Never.

115
00:09:35,120 --> 00:09:37,320
If I knew about music
as much as you do,

116
00:09:37,640 --> 00:09:39,160
I'd make music all the time.

117
00:09:39,960 --> 00:09:42,160
- You wouldn't get anywhere.
- Why not?

118
00:09:42,400 --> 00:09:45,320
You are a letter-carrier
not a composer.

119
00:09:45,800 --> 00:09:48,080
You think a letter-carrier
can't make music?

120
00:09:48,280 --> 00:09:50,320
- Of course not.
- Someone did.

121
00:09:50,520 --> 00:09:52,280
- Did what?
- A song.

122
00:09:52,520 --> 00:09:54,400
- Who?
- A letter-carrier.

123
00:09:54,840 --> 00:09:57,040
I can imagine. Who?

124
00:09:57,280 --> 00:09:59,600
- You don't know her.
- Not Zinka?

125
00:09:59,760 --> 00:10:02,440
No, not Zinka.
It's my friend, Dunya.

126
00:10:02,360 --> 00:10:04,240
I can imagine.

127
00:10:04,440 --> 00:10:08,240
What's so funny? First hear it,
then laugh.

128
00:10:08,640 --> 00:10:11,360
- Okay.
- Hey, toss me the accordion.

129
00:10:19,840 --> 00:10:22,880
Many a song has been sung
'bout the Volga.

130
00:10:23,400 --> 00:10:26,320
But the best one is yet
to be sung

131
00:10:27,040 --> 00:10:30,160
That would fly across
our Mother Volga

132
00:10:30,840 --> 00:10:33,560
In the bright rays
of our Soviet sun.

133
00:10:34,240 --> 00:10:37,160
O Volga, so beautiful,

134
00:10:37,600 --> 00:10:40,240
Like sea, you're full
and plentiful,

135
00:10:40,800 --> 00:10:43,960
Like life
you're free and bountiful,

136
00:10:44,720 --> 00:10:47,080
You are wide, deep and
powerful.

137
00:10:51,360 --> 00:10:54,000
Tell your Dunya she's a fool.

138
00:10:55,600 --> 00:10:58,480
- Well, really.
- Yes, really. I mean you...

139
00:10:59,400 --> 00:11:02,040
...in your group are just
fooling around.

140
00:11:02,280 --> 00:11:04,040
Fooling around?

141
00:11:04,160 --> 00:11:07,920
Uncle Kuzya plays the selfmade
trumpet better than you play.

142
00:11:08,120 --> 00:11:11,640
Kuzya plays better?
Some player!

143
00:11:12,520 --> 00:11:15,480
You've got a nice ensemble
uncle Kuzya, aunt Pasha,

144
00:11:15,720 --> 00:11:17,880
and now Dunya, a kind of
composer.

145
00:11:18,400 --> 00:11:21,120
An instrumental ensemble
"Make a cat laugh".

146
00:11:21,800 --> 00:11:25,400
Make a cat laugh? Well,
if you want my opinion,

147
00:11:25,720 --> 00:11:29,760
your orchestra is fit to play
in a milk shop in summer.

148
00:11:29,960 --> 00:11:32,680
- Why is that?
- All flies will die.

149
00:11:32,880 --> 00:11:34,440
Flies will die?

150
00:11:34,560 --> 00:11:37,400
There'll be neither flies,
nor the milkshop.

151
00:11:38,120 --> 00:11:40,640
Milk will turn sour from
your voices.

152
00:11:41,080 --> 00:11:43,320
Milk will turn sour?

153
00:11:46,160 --> 00:11:47,840
Comrade Byvalov!

154
00:11:50,280 --> 00:11:51,800
Comrade Byvalov!

155
00:11:53,760 --> 00:11:58,360
- What do you want?
- The letter-carrier has a cable for you.

156
00:11:58,520 --> 00:12:00,240
Give it to me.

157
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:03,560
- Where is it?
- In the river.

158
00:12:04,040 --> 00:12:07,560
- Why in the river?
- Why, the ferry got stuck.

159
00:12:08,120 --> 00:12:09,480
Dammit.

160
00:12:10,200 --> 00:12:11,680
Send a boat there.

161
00:12:12,040 --> 00:12:15,240
The boats are being caulked
and can't be launched.

162
00:12:15,480 --> 00:12:16,880
Okhapkin!

163
00:12:18,080 --> 00:12:19,400
Okhapkin!

164
00:12:21,040 --> 00:12:22,840
- Here I am.
- Pick up the receiver.

165
00:12:23,080 --> 00:12:25,880
- Why?
- I'm gonna speak to you.

166
00:12:27,120 --> 00:12:29,040
My pleasure, I don't mind.

167
00:12:33,360 --> 00:12:35,280
Hello. Garage?

168
00:12:36,360 --> 00:12:38,120
Harness your mare.

169
00:12:39,480 --> 00:12:41,240
Harness your mare I say.

170
00:12:41,480 --> 00:12:42,760
Dammit.

171
00:12:42,960 --> 00:12:44,640
Harness your mare!

172
00:12:45,840 --> 00:12:47,360
Mare?

173
00:12:50,960 --> 00:12:52,240
How?

174
00:12:53,680 --> 00:12:54,960
I don't get it.

175
00:12:55,880 --> 00:12:57,520
What are you trying to say?

176
00:12:57,720 --> 00:13:00,600
The mare got unshod.
It needs shoeing.

177
00:13:01,360 --> 00:13:02,760
For shame!

178
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:05,720
Moscow wants me and their mares
get unshod.

179
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:09,960
- Okay. Hang up.
- My pleasure, I don't mind.

180
00:13:14,560 --> 00:13:17,520
It's ridiculous. I just want
to fret and fume.

181
00:13:19,480 --> 00:13:21,160
Hold it, hold it.

182
00:13:24,720 --> 00:13:27,240
Zoya, get the citizens' defectives

183
00:13:27,480 --> 00:13:29,160
and give them others.

184
00:13:29,360 --> 00:13:31,120
Citizens, follow me.

185
00:13:47,960 --> 00:13:49,920
Water
Beer

186
00:13:56,600 --> 00:13:58,680
Gee-up! Gee-up!

187
00:14:00,960 --> 00:14:04,240
Don't waste your breath.
She won't budge.

188
00:14:04,480 --> 00:14:05,840
Why not?

189
00:14:06,240 --> 00:14:10,520
She's used to stopping dead here
since early childhood.

190
00:14:13,800 --> 00:14:16,760
Until you treat her to some bread
and salt

191
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:18,920
she won't move.

192
00:14:20,080 --> 00:14:24,600
I've been driving her for 15 years

193
00:14:25,040 --> 00:14:29,640
but I still don't have a clue
who taught her that.

194
00:14:37,240 --> 00:14:39,520
Here's a funny question, man:

195
00:14:41,520 --> 00:14:43,920
why am I a waterman?

196
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:48,680
Without water everywhere

197
00:14:51,600 --> 00:14:54,560
You get neither here,
nor there.

198
00:15:17,160 --> 00:15:19,560
We drink water on vacations,

199
00:15:21,600 --> 00:15:24,160
Watery are our sessions.

200
00:15:26,360 --> 00:15:29,520
So without water everywhere

201
00:15:32,760 --> 00:15:35,760
You get neither here,
nor there.

202
00:15:41,160 --> 00:15:44,840
Bread and salt is a psychosis
with this gelding.

203
00:15:53,340 --> 00:15:55,220
My bandmen are no match
for your buffoons.

204
00:15:56,900 --> 00:16:00,300
Mine are cultured musicians.
No one beneath an accountant.

205
00:16:01,620 --> 00:16:04,620
- It's a Neapolitan band.
- Neapolitan?

206
00:16:04,860 --> 00:16:07,900
How strange. I thought it was
a double Italian one.

207
00:16:08,300 --> 00:16:11,140
The accountants play and you
conduct with a ruler.

208
00:16:12,580 --> 00:16:14,500
You are an office drudge.

209
00:16:15,060 --> 00:16:17,580
Me a drudge? And you... you...

210
00:16:18,220 --> 00:16:20,140
You are another,
you are another.

211
00:16:20,660 --> 00:16:22,100
Fool!

212
00:16:28,620 --> 00:16:29,900
Ferry ahoy!

213
00:16:30,980 --> 00:16:32,340
Ay-ay!

214
00:16:32,660 --> 00:16:34,140
Where is the cable?

215
00:16:35,020 --> 00:16:36,460
Right here.

216
00:16:39,220 --> 00:16:40,700
Read it.

217
00:16:43,940 --> 00:16:46,540
Moscow wants...

218
00:16:47,860 --> 00:16:49,260
Moscow...

219
00:16:51,700 --> 00:16:55,820
What did I say? Read on.

220
00:16:58,620 --> 00:17:00,500
Frustration...

221
00:17:01,820 --> 00:17:03,900
Participation...

222
00:17:05,220 --> 00:17:07,140
I can't hear you.

223
00:17:09,660 --> 00:17:11,580
In chorus, comrades.

224
00:17:13,980 --> 00:17:15,780
Participation!

225
00:17:25,620 --> 00:17:27,580
They want participation.

226
00:17:28,420 --> 00:17:29,820
Participation?

227
00:17:30,300 --> 00:17:33,980
No can do, comrades.
I am going to Moscow.

228
00:17:34,580 --> 00:17:37,740
- Ask my deputy.
- Participation...

229
00:17:38,300 --> 00:17:40,260
...Olympiad...

230
00:17:40,580 --> 00:17:43,100
...amateur arts.

231
00:17:46,100 --> 00:17:48,260
I don't get it.

232
00:17:49,180 --> 00:17:51,620
Delegation of your

233
00:17:53,020 --> 00:17:55,020
staff workers.

234
00:18:00,260 --> 00:18:02,460
A good beginning,

235
00:18:03,460 --> 00:18:05,460
"Moscow wants"

236
00:18:06,740 --> 00:18:08,980
but a lousy ending,

237
00:18:10,220 --> 00:18:11,660
"amateur arts".

238
00:18:15,100 --> 00:18:17,260
Anything else?

239
00:18:18,220 --> 00:18:20,100
Nothing. This is it.

240
00:18:26,540 --> 00:18:27,900
I'll answer.

241
00:18:29,180 --> 00:18:30,540
I'll ans...

242
00:18:36,580 --> 00:18:38,620
Hey Kuzma.

243
00:18:39,660 --> 00:18:42,060
Shout "I'll answer" with me.

244
00:18:42,820 --> 00:18:44,420
- I'll answer?
- Yes.

245
00:18:44,940 --> 00:18:46,780
- With you?
- Yes, yes.

246
00:18:46,940 --> 00:18:48,740
My voice...

247
00:18:48,980 --> 00:18:51,500
You've bungled it all

248
00:18:51,820 --> 00:18:53,940
and I will answer with you
for it?

249
00:18:54,300 --> 00:18:58,100
You just shout and I
will answer.

250
00:18:59,060 --> 00:19:02,780
If I shout and you answer,
it's a deal.

251
00:19:03,500 --> 00:19:05,820
In those merry days of old...

252
00:19:08,020 --> 00:19:09,380
Why are you shouting?

253
00:19:09,620 --> 00:19:12,020
Why not if you are going
to answer for it.

254
00:19:12,340 --> 00:19:15,940
Shout just what I will say.

255
00:19:16,660 --> 00:19:18,500
Shout "My reply".

256
00:19:19,300 --> 00:19:20,580
My reply.

257
00:19:21,740 --> 00:19:24,420
Shout now "top secret".

258
00:19:25,660 --> 00:19:28,940
Shout now top secret!

259
00:19:30,340 --> 00:19:32,460
Don't shout "shout now".

260
00:19:32,740 --> 00:19:35,940
Not to shout now?
When do I shout?

261
00:19:36,220 --> 00:19:39,060
Shout now, but don't shout now
"shout now",

